"{\"uid\": \"thesouthafrican.com-sport-paris-olympics-2024-breaking-tatjana-smith-posts-fastest-time-in-200m-breaststroke-heats-result-exclusive\", \"text\": \"Copyright Blue Sky Publications (Pty) Ltd. All Rights Reserved.  thesouthafrican.com is a division of Blue Sky Publications Ltd. Reproduction without permission prohibited  Home\\u00bbSport\\u00bbParis Olympics 2024\\u00bbBREAKING: Tatjana Smith posts fastest time in 200m breaststroke heats  Tatjana Smith wasted no time in living up to her billing as the favourite for the women's 200m breaststroke gold medal at the Paris Olympics.  South Africa'sTatjana Smithwasted no time in living up to her billing as the favourite for the women's200m breaststrokegold medal at theParis Olympics 2024on Wednesday morning.  Enjoy the Paris Olympic Games 2024 experience at your favourite ATKV Resort!  Smith, swimming in Heat 1 of the event, posted thefastest overall timeof2:21:57.  Team South Africa's second entrant in the event,Kaylene Corbett, finished second in the same heat as Smith in a time of2:23:85which wound up as thesixthfastest overall when all was said and done.  Smith is the defending Olympic champion in the 200m breaststroke having won in Tokyo in 2021.  Only23swimmers took to the starting blocks for the heats which saw the top 16 qualify for the semi-finals starting at21:51(SA time), also on Wednesday, 31 July.  The top 8 will race the final onThursday, 1 Augustat21:04(SA time).  Meanwhile, as reported byThe South African website, Tatjana Smith\\u00a0took victory in the women's 100m breaststroke at the\\u00a0Paris Olympics 2024\\u00a0on Monday evening, giving South Africa its first gold medal of the Games.  Smith touched the wall in a time of1:05:28, finishing ahead of China'sQianting Tang(1:05:54), with Ireland'sMona McSharryin third (1:05.59).  Tributes were quick to pour in, including fromchicken fast food chain Nando's.  With her 100m breaststroke win, Smith becameSouth Africa's greatest ever Olympianwith two gold medals and a silver (and counting \\u2026)  Should Smith win the 200m breaststroke gold medal,she would emulatecompatriotPenny Heynswho completed the 100m-200m breaststroke golden double at the 1996 Olympics in Atlanta.  Smith pocketedR400 000for her win in the women's 100m breaststroke thanks to the financial incentives promised by theSouth African Sports Confederation and Olympic Committee (Sascoc).  Smith's coach, Rocco Meiring, will earn R100 000 for his role's in Smith's victory.  IndividualsGold medallists R400 000 and the coach R100 000Silver medallists R200 000 and the coach R50 000Bronze medallists R75 000 and the coach R25 000  In addition, as reported byThe South African website, new Minister of Sport, Arts and Culture,Gayton McKenzie, promised that he has a 'big surprise' for all Team SA medal winners, suggesting there could be more prize money coming their way.  For the latest Paris Olympics 2024 news, bookmarkThe South African website'sdedicated section for free-to-read content  WIN R2 000: Take The South African's SASSA Survey  The South African is hiring! Freelance writing positions available  Follow The South African on Facebook for the latest local and international news  Follow The South African's WhatsApp channel for the latest sport, lifestyle and local news  Follow The South African on X for the latest, breaking news  A brand new shopping mall is coming to Pretoria East, bringing major retailers and new convenience to the area.  Orlando Pirates are reportedly set to welcome a new staff member in former Stellenbosch FC Head of Recruitment Brendon Fourie.  Masindi Nemtajela was stretched off during Orlando Pirates' 6-0 win over TS Galaxy on Sunday afternoon in Mbombela.  IT support is not just technical, it is personal.  Liema Pantsi's victory was clouded as fans of the 'Big Brother Mzansi' show expressed that Smash Afrika was unprofessional towards her.  A dominant weekend for the SA teams in the URC has made a big impact on the latest log standings as the playoffs edge closer.    TheSouthAfrican.com is all about South Africa and the stories that affect South Africans, wherever they are in the world.  We are independent.No agenda.No bias.  Our offices are for administrative purposes only, no visitors will be accepted without an appointment.  South Africa- Blue Sky Publications (Pty) Ltd - Registration Number: 2005/028472/07 - Address: Regus Business Centre, 1st Floor, Block B, North Park, Black River Park, 2 Fir Street, Observatory, Cape Town, 7925, South Africa  Copyright Blue Sky Publications (Pty) Ltd. All Rights Reserved.\"}"